<P>Mr. <HI>Garrick</HI> acquie&s;ced to the former part o<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> his confe&s;&s;ion; and told him that but poor mat<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">+rials for the &s;tage could be derived from the la<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">+ter. This is the up&s;hot of his crime. Has h<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">
<PB N="19" REF="18">then de&s;erved all the foul-mouthed abu&s;e that has been lavi&s;hed on him? I think not, who am not partial to him.</P>
<P>The pulpit and clergy of <HI>Scotland</HI> are irreve|rently treated in the <HI>analy&s;is,</HI> which ends with a bullying line, that might waggi&s;hly be retorted, to wit,
<Q><L>The blood of <HI>Douglas</HI> will <HI>defend</HI> it&s;elf,</L></Q></P>
